SIMPLE: ribaldry
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ribaldry
<hw>Rib"ald*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>ribaldrie</ets>, <ets>ribaudrie</ets>, OF. <ets>ribalderie</ets>,
<ets>ribauderie</ets>.]</ety> <def>The talk of a ribald; low, vulgar
language; indecency; obscenity; lewdness; -- now chiefly applied to
indecent language, but formerly, as by Chaucer, also to indecent acts or
conduct.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>ribaldry</qex> of his conversation moved astonishment
even in that age.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Riban</ent>⟦br⟧
